comment:
Maybe I‚Äôm in the minority here, but I‚Äôll say it. Just because Sony, Fox, and Disney are three separate movie studios, does NOT mean the in-story explanation has to be that the characters in the respective three are in their own distinct universe.

Case in point, I thought the post-credit Venom scene in No Way Home was unnecessary, as there‚Äôs no reason for Sony to put themselves in that hole rather than have the implication that Tom Holland‚Äôs Spider-man is somewhere out there in that world, just offscreen & not referenced.

That being said, just because MCU acquired the rights to Deadpool, does NOT mean there needs to be in-story explanation of him traveling from Fox-verse to Marvel-verse and bringing Wolverine with him through a portal. I‚Äôm all for him referencing it breaking the fourth wall, but actually doing it as a major part of the plot is another story.

The most grounded way of doing it is to imply the X-men, Deadpool, and Wolverine have been in the same world alongside other Marvel characters all along. Just because past X-men instalments didn‚Äôt reference them before, that‚Äôs perfectly fine.

The idea of characters switching universes because they change movie studios is absurd and unnecessary. The early Jason movies were distributed by Paramount. Then it switched to New Line Cinema. They never showed Jason hopping into a New Line portal so he could fight Freddy Krueger. üòÇ

I‚Äôm tired of multiverse stories. They‚Äôre great every vicennium as a nostalgic treat, but as a plot device for every other movie, they must go. They make the writer‚Äôs job very easy because they‚Äôre are infinite possibilities. There are no real threats and stake because a character can hop on over to Fox-verse and nab an alternate version of someone who just died. Iron Man‚Äôs death has no meaning really since they can nab a new one over in Sony-verse who happens to look like Tom Cruise. Nothing matters.

Now, compare to a story like in ‚ÄúThe Batman‚Äù which has a grounded story without portals and potions to fill a 3-hour runtime where real things are at stake. When people die they die. These stories are harder to write. As I said, the multiverse can be fun, but it needs to go as a plot device. Ever since No Way Home, it‚Äôs being used too much.

comment:
And that was me disqualifying, cancelling, wiping away, de-indexing, closing, ignoring, yelling, yawning at every single suggestion of that trailer as yet another quality fan-made trailer, believing Jackman was (sadly) a man of his word when it came to Logan's ultimate fate in the film of the same name, that happened to be one of the most disturbing, obscure and mature iterations of the franchise's darkest timeline yet.

And then, I watched. And my mind exploded. Texting and sending frenetic audios to all my fan friends that laugh back at me since I'm SO late to the party.

I clicked on this trailer posted on a non-official channel believing I would at least enjoy a quality artist view of what "could have been in another Earth". I dreamed, hoped, waiting, thought, obsessed so many times, in so many forms, for so many years, randomly googling any piece of news that could have the slightest connection to such a revival that I had somehow completely made peace with leaving the most glorious past where it belonged, behind us, with our best memories to cherish about it.

And suddenly, the OFFICIAL Wolverine jumped, roared, swore, drank, was such a marvelous piece of tortured trash again and then shined on the savage battlefied, with non other than Reynold's Deadpool.

This cannot be real.

Yet, it is.

I , LOVE, MY, SILLY, DAY.

comment: OK so here are my speculations. Based on both trailers, we see Deadpool approaching a Wolverine dressed up as "patch" in the first trailer, and then in this one we see him approaching Wolverine in a bar (possibly for the first time) so I'm thinking that at least 2 different Wolverines (Variants) confirmed. The TVA recruits Deadpool because of his healing factor and his fighting skills because they are AFRAID of approaching any Wolverine variants to capture them (for whatever reason) so they need Deadpool's help with that because he's the only one who can do it (fight a Wolverine variant and survive), now I'm expecting that the TVA tricks Deadpool because we see him killing TVA agents in the trailer so they either lie to him about why they want these Wolverine variants captured/pruned, or he just discovers something he doesn't like right after he succeeds in capturing Wolverine because we see him lying on the ground so either way Deadpool ends up turning against them but he and this Wolverine get pruned as well and get sent to the Void at the end of time (where we see the 20th century fox logo) because we also see Alioth (the cloudy looking creature) in the trailer which we saw for the first time in the LOKI series. Now we also hear Deadpool saying ("I'm about to lose everything that I ever cared about" and "I don't know anything about saving worlds") and I did say earlier that he discovers something he doesn't like so that could be that he discovers that the TVA wants to prune/erase his reality (Deadpool's reality)!! So that means Vanessa, Dopinder, Al, and all the others that we see in the trailer will be gone forever and it's possibly because in his last movie Deadpool went back in time to save Vanessa (which is something that he's not supposed to do based on how the TVA works) so Deadpool starts to try and convince Wolverine to help him save his world (giving him a chance for redemption for failing to save his own) as well as finding a way to get out of the void and back to the TVA to stop them in time. I don't know if the Dr. Strange portal has anything to do with getting them out or not but they will be encountering lots of characters along the way possibly other variants. But the real villain here is the TVA. At least that's what I think, but I could be wrong though. Either way I think at least some of it is real based on what the trailer shows.
